UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2382
1 pupils or providing moral instruction to students through the offering;
2 (b) A statement acknowledging and agreeing to be bound by the requirements
3 placed upon moral instruction offerings under this section;
4 (c) The address or a description of the location where the moral instruction will
5 be provided;
6 (d) A transportation plan to ensure the safety of pupils while traveling to and
7 from moral instruction within the allotted time period;
8 (e) A statement acknowledging and agreeing to inform the parent or guardian of a
9 participating pupil that the school district and its employees and agents shall
10 not incur any liability as a result of any injury sustained by the pupil related to
11 participation in the moral instruction offering;
12 (f) A statement acknowledging and agreeing to indemnify and hold harmless the
13 school district and its employees and agents against any claims relating to the
14 moral instruction offering or transportation to or from the offering; and
15 (g) Proof of insurance coverage to be carried by the provider that shall include
16 adequate insurance for liability, property loss, and personal injury of students
17 related to the moral instruction offering or transportation to or from the
18 offering.
19 (4) (a) Upon receipt of a plan that complies with the requirements
20 established[request] under subsection (3) of this section, the local board of
21 education shall[may] make arrangements with the person seeking to provide
22 the moral instruction offering as the local board deems necessary to facilitate
23 pupil participation in the moral instruction offering.
24 (b) Upon approval by the local board of a plan[request] under this section, the
25 superintendent of the school district shall require each individual identified in
26 the plan[request] to submit to a national and state criminal history background
27 check by the Department of Kentucky State Police and the Federal Bureau of
Page 2 of 5
XXXX 3/3/2026 10:51 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2382
1 Investigation and have a clear CA/N check, provided by the individual,
2 consistent with the provisions of KRS 160.380(6). The individuals, or the
3 organization or entity through which the moral instruction offering will be
4 provided, shall be responsible for all costs associated with obtaining the
5 criminal history and CA/N checks under this paragraph.
6 (c) As a condition of the agreement between the local board and a provider, the
7 local board shall require that any individual identified in the plan[request]
8 under subsection (3) of this section be barred from providing transportation or
9 participating in moral instruction offerings under this section upon receipt by
10 the school district of a report documenting a record of:
11 1. Child abuse or neglect;
12 2. A sex crime or criminal offense against a victim who is a minor, as
13 defined in KRS 17.500; or
14 3. A violent crime as defined in KRS 17.165;
15 by the individual. The prohibition shall continue until the local board receives
16 an updated record for that individual that does not contain a disqualifying
17 item.
18 (5) A pupil who attends a moral instruction offering at the time specified and for the
19 period fixed shall be:
20 (a) Credited with the time of attendance as if he or she had been in actual
21 attendance in school, and the time shall be included as part of the actual
22 school work required in KRS 158.060. A pupil shall not be penalized for any
23 school work missed during the specified time; and
24 (b) Included in calculating the average daily attendance for the Support Education
25 Excellence in Kentucky program as if the pupil was in actual attendance in
26 school.
27 (6) A pupil who does not participate in a moral instruction offering shall remain in
Page 3 of 5
XXXX 3/3/2026 10:51 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2382
1 school during the time when the instruction is being given[, and shall take noncredit
2 enrichment courses or participate in educational activities not required in the
3 regular curriculum, and that time shall be included as part of the actual school work
4 required in KRS 158.060. Students of different grade levels may be placed into
5 combined classrooms in accordance with maximum class size allotments as
6 described in KRS 157.360. These courses or activities shall be supervised by
7 certified school personnel and may include but are not limited to study hall,
8 computer instruction, music, art, library, physical education, and tutorial
9 assistance].
10 (7) A school district shall not discriminate against a pupil for his or her participation or
11 nonparticipation in a moral instruction offering.
12 (8) (a) Each local board of education shall submit the following information
13 quarterly to the Kentucky Department of Education:
14 1. The name of each person[applicant] that submitted a plan[request] to
15 provide a moral instruction offering;
16 2. The date of the plan submission[application];
17 3. The local board's approval or denial of the plan[application]; and
18 4. If the plan[request] was denied, the area or areas of noncompliance
19 with the requirements established under subsection (3) that
20 caused[reason for] the denial.
21 (b) The Kentucky Department of Education shall compile the quarterly reports
22 required by this subsection and submit a combined report to the Legislative
23 Research Commission no later than December 1 of each year for referral to
24 the appropriate Interim Joint Committee on Education.
25 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 158 IS CREATED TO
26 READ AS FOLLOWS:
27 (1) The Attorney General may bring a civil action for a writ of mandamus to compel
Page 4 of 5
XXXX 3/3/2026 10:51 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2382
1 a local board of education to comply with Section 1 of this Act and subsection (3)
2 of this section.
3 (2) (a) Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, a qualified individual
4 may bring a civil action for injunctive relief from a violation of Section 1 of
5 this Act or subsection (3) of this section.
6 (b) Sovereign, governmental, and qualified immunity are waived for the limited
7 purpose of bringing a claim filed under this subsection and arising from a
8 violation of Section 1 of this Act or subsection (3) of this section.
9 (c) A qualified individual may recover reasonable and actual attorney's fees
10 and litigation costs upon proving, by clear and convincing evidence, that a
11 defendant intentionally and willfully violated Section 1 of this Act or
12 subsection (3) of this section.
13 (d) The remedies identified in this subsection shall be in addition to and not in
14 lieu of any other remedies available at law or equity.
15 (3) An employee or agent of a local board of education shall not use, or threaten the
16 use of, any official authority or influence to discourage, interfere with, or
17 otherwise retaliate against any individual who in good faith files, supports, aids,
18 or otherwise participates in a civil action filed in accordance with subsection (2)
19 of this section.
